The Board on Mathematical Sciences and Analytics (BMSA) and the Committee on Applied and Theoretical Statistics (CATS) of the National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine organize studies, workshops, and other activities that advise and inform government agencies, research communities, and industry. Through these activities, BMSA and CATS help a range of federal agencies engage with and make better use of the mathematical sciences and collaborate with research and education communities.  More broadly, BMSA and CATS activities help improve policymaking, increase appreciation for the mathematical sciences, expand research funding for the mathematical sciences, and create long-lasting partnerships that connect diverse communities and topics.

The subject award supported quarterly meetings for BMSA and CATS as well as preparations for and follow-through from these meetings. These meetings provided opportunities to connect BMSA and CATS members with representatives from federal agencies to discuss challenges and opportunities in U.S. science policymaking. This award also provided support for the active engagement of BMSA and CATS members in the science policy community, notably resulting in a greater number of mathematicians and statisticians contributing to a wide range of activities at the National Academies. These efforts broaden the influence and impact of the mathematical and statistical sciences among other academic communities and their stakeholders.

This award also supported:

The "Mathematical Frontiers" monthly webinar series that informed a general audience about mathematical achievements and open challenges on a variety topics;
Booths and talks at several national conferences; and
 Symposia on (1) Data, Modeling, and Policy Making to Address the Opioid Epidemic and (2) Data Collection and Integration to Enhance Public Health.


During this performance period, BMSA and CATS initiated and/or oversaw the following separately-funded activities:

A study on risk analysis for nuclear terrorism and nuclear war;
A study on illustrating the impact of the mathematical sciences;
A study on improving defense acquisition workforce capability in data use;
A study on multidisciplinary evidence base for national ambient air quality standards;
A workshop on mathematical approaches to optimize infrastructure investments for sustainability;
A study on forecasting costs for preserving, archiving, and promoting access to biomedical data;
A roundtable on data science postsecondary education;
A workshop on enhancing urban sustainability with data, modeling, and simulation;
A workshop on data-driven modeling for additive manufacturing of metals; and
The #ElevatingMath video competitions for early career researchers and students.


NSF core support was critical for scoping and initiating these activities.

